<p>MCLG = Maximum Contaminant Level Goal
<p style="text-align: center">Table 1. Water quality standards of a few elements
<p style="text-align: right">(http://hppcb.gov.in/eiasorang/spec.pdf)

<p><b>Laboratory work: -</b> 
<p style="margin-left: 150px;">(i) Determination of pH
<br>(ii) BOD
<br>(iii) COD
<br>(iv) Dissolved pollutants and salts

<p><b>Water quality parameters and indicators: -</b> 
<p style="margin-left: 150px;">1. <u>Temperatures</u>: - Temperature is important as it affects the amount of oxygen dissolved in it.
<br>2. <u>Salinity</u>
<br>3. <u>pH</u>
<p style="margin-left: 200px;">it is measured by using a calorimetric test.
<br>Litmus paper, phenolphthalein, methyl orange, or universal indicator can be used.
<br>Acceptable pH value is 6.5 to 8.5 on pH scale.
<p style="margin-left: 150px;">4. <u>BOD (Biochemical Oxygen Demand) and COD (Chemical Oxygen Demand)</u>: -
<p style="margin-left: 200px;">Under it, oxygen amount dissolved in H<sub>2</sub>O is measured. It is variable in temperature.
<p style="margin-left: 150px;">5. <u>Specific Conductance</u>
<p style="text-align: right">(http://www.lcra.org/water/quality/crwn/indicators.html)
